'''Stan Lee''' was a [[Star Wars comic books|comic book]] writer, editor, and publisher. For decades he was the most visible leader at [[Marvel Comics]].

His involvement with [[Star Wars (1977)|''Marvel Star Wars'']] was limited but significant. In [[1977]] he was serving as the publisher of Marvel Comics. He originally planned to decline making a series based on the movie ''[[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|Star Wars]],'' believing it to be just another science-fiction film; however, after learning [[Alec Guinness|Sir Alec Guinness]] was involved, he was intrigued. This allowed [[Roy Thomas]] to talk him into it,<ref name="Comics Introduction">''[[The Marvel Comics Illustrated Version of Star Wars]]''</ref> a decision credited by many with saving Marvel Comics from financial bankruptcy.<ref name="Saved>*{{SWArchive|url=episode-iv/bts/article/f20070601/index.html|text=''Star Wars'': The Comic Book That Saved Marvel!}}</ref> 

Stan Lee wrote the introduction to ''[[The Marvel Comics Illustrated Version of Star Wars]]'', which collected the six-issue adaptation of the film.<ref name="Comics Introduction" /> In [[1985]], Marvel UK reprinted two of Lee's science fiction comics, both written in [[1960s#1963|1963]], in [[Return of the Jedi Weekly 83|''Return of the Jedi Weekly'' 83]] and ''[[Star Wars Summer Special 1985]]''. They were labeled "[[R2-D2's tales from the Data Banks]]" despite having no particular connection to ''Star Wars''.<ref name="Stan Lee and Artoo">{{SW|url=news/stan-lee-and-artoos-astonishing-adventures|text=Stan Lee and Artoo's Astonishing Adventures}}</ref>

Lee passed away following severe illness on [[November 12]], [[2018]].<ref name="TMZ">{{WebCite|url=https://www.tmz.com/2018/11/12/stan-lee-dead-dies-marvel-comics|text=Stan Lee Dead at 95|date=2018-11-12|archivedate=20200902075607}}</ref>

